<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="175" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="24.[132,775,880,930]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">
<collectionCode box="[132,258,880,903]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">
<typeStatus box="[132,181,880,903]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">TYPE</typeStatus>
SPECIES
</collectionCode>
. — 
<taxonomicName authority="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin, 2017" authorityName="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin" authorityYear="2017" box="[300,477,880,904]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Paguriscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus" status="n. gen., n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[300,477,880,904]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Paguriscus robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[483,615,880,904]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" rank="species">n. gen., n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, by present designation. Gender: masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="175" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[132,775,955,1059]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">
ETYMOLOGY. — The generic name is derived from the genus name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1775" box="[132,206,982,1005]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Pagurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[132,206,982,1005]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Pagurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and using the masculine Greek suffix - 
<emphasis box="[588,629,982,1005]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">iscus</emphasis>
which denotes something diminutive, in reference to the minute size of specimens in the single species of this new genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="175" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[131,777,1093,1435]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">
DIAGNOSIS. — Eight pairs of biserial phyllobranch gills, no pleurobranchs on somites X, XI, XII (thoracomeres 5-7, above pereopods 2-4). Rostrum triangular. Ocular acicles simple. Crista dentata with accessory tooth. Chelipeds presumably unequal [left missing in 
<typeStatus box="[161,249,1199,1223]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">holotype</typeStatus>
and single specimen known]. Sternite of somite XI (thoracomere 6, pereopod 3) with semi-circular anterior lobe. Pereopod 4 with single row of scales on propodal rasp, dactyl lacking preungual process. Pereopod 5 semi-chelate. Male with coxae of pereopods 5 slightly asymmetrical, trapezoidal in shape, extending posteriorly to form themselves paired sexual tubes; with unpaired, left pleopods 3-5. Telson nearly symmetrical, with weak or obsolete lateral indentations; terminal margins of posterior lobes oblique, with shallow median cleft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="175" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="24.[132,775,1459,1509]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">
DISTRIBUTION. — Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[541,583,1459,1483]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">type</typeStatus>
species collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[132,254,1485,1509]" name="Guadeloupe" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Guadeloupe</collectingCountry>
, Lesser Antilles, Caribbean Sea, at a depth of 
<specimenCount box="[699,758,1485,1509]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" type="generic">
<quantity box="[699,754,1485,1509]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" unit="m" value="19.0">19 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="175" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[130,776,1555,2028]" box="[132,232,1555,1581]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[130,776,1555,2028]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">
Despite the incompleteness of the single male specimen of the new species herein described for this new genus, there is sufficient justification for a new genus based on the unusual low gill number (eight) and formula (lacking pleurobranchs), and by the morphology of the coxae and sexual tubes of pereopods 
<quantity box="[252,294,1746,1773]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
this male. In pagurids, the number of gills is known to vary from 8 to 13 pairs, with the majority having 11. Previous to the discovery of this new genus, only one pagurid species 
<taxonomicName authority="McLaughlin, 1997" authorityName="McLaughlin" authorityYear="1997" box="[306,770,1841,1868]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Decaphyllus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barunajaya">
<emphasis box="[306,555,1841,1867]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Decaphyllus barunajaya</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="MCLAUGHLIN P. A." box="[563,770,1841,1868]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" pagination="433 - 572" refId="ref25463" refString="MCLAUGHLIN P. A. 1997. - Crustacea Decapoda: Hermit crabs of the family Paguridae from the KARUBAR cruise in Indonesia, in CROSNIER A. &amp; BOUCHET P. (eds), Resultats des Campagnes MUSOR- STOM volume 16. Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, Paris: 433 - 572 (Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle; 172)." type="book chapter" year="1997">McLaughlin, 1997</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, was known to have eight pairs of gills. However, in 
<taxonomicName authority="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin, 2017" authorityName="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin" authorityYear="2017" box="[669,775,1874,1899]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Paguriscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[669,775,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Paguriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[132,208,1906,1932]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, there are two arthrobranchs on the third maxilliped, and all pleurobranchs have been lost, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McLaughlin" authorityYear="1997" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Decaphyllus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barunajaya">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">D. barunajaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are no arthrobranchs on the third maxilliped, and pleurobranchs are present on pereopods 3 and 4.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[810,1457,215,561]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">
The posteriorly projecting, and slightly asymmetrical coxae of pereopods 
<quantity box="[958,1001,247,274]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
the male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin, 2017" authorityName="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin" authorityYear="2017" box="[1134,1244,248,273]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Paguriscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1134,1244,248,273]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Paguriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1249,1324,248,274]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation box="[1337,1439,247,274]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="25.[132,143,1963,1981]" captionTargetBox="[226,1365,231,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-15@25.[214,1381,214,1813]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIG. 16. — Paguriscus robustus n. gen., n. sp., holotype ♂ 1.3 mm, Guadeloupe, sta GS 20, MNHN-IU-2013-4395: A, shield and cephalic appendages, dorsal view; B, right pereopod 3, lateral view; C, dactyl of same, mesial view; D, sternite XI of third pereopods, ventral view; E, propodus and dactyl of right pereopod 4, lateral view; F, telson, dorsal view; G, coxae of pereopods 5, sternite XIII, and anterior part of pleon, ventral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5391938" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5391938/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Fig. 16G</figureCitation>
), is an unusual condition among genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[1286,1395,279,305]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Paguridae</taxonomicName>
with sexual tubes. In other pagurids with male sexual tubes, these are present as clearly separate structures from the coxae, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authority="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin, 2017" authorityName="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin" authorityYear="2017" box="[937,1047,375,400]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Paguriscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[937,1047,375,400]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Paguriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1053,1129,375,401]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
each coxa consists of a single, calcified tube-like piece. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin, 2017" authorityName="Lemaitre &amp; Felder &amp; Poupin" authorityYear="2017" box="[1113,1223,407,432]" class="Malacostraca" family="Paguridae" genus="Paguriscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1113,1223,407,432]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="175">Paguriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1228,1305,407,433]" pageId="24" pageNumber="175" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, the coxae are somewhat similar to the solid, one-piece coxal extensions of males in some coenobitids (see Tudge &amp; Lemaitre 2006), although the similarity can be attributed to evolutionary convergence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
